, England","Blo'norton, Norfolk, England":"Blo'norton, Norfolk, England"},"nl":{"1400–":"1400–Overleden","1400–Male":"1400–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1405–Female":"1405–Overleden","1422–Female":"1422–Overleden","1375–1413":"1375–1413","–Female":"Overleden","1413":"1413","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1455":"1455","1421":"1421","1399":"1399","1375":"1375","1405":"1405","Hales, Norfolk, England":"Hales, Norfolk, England","Wood Norton, Norfolk, England":"Wood Norton, Norfolk, England","Blo'norton, Norfolk, England":"Blo'norton, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"1400–":"1400–Deceased","1400–Male":"1400–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1405–Female":"1405–Deceased","1422–Female":"1422–Deceased","1375–1413":"1375–1413","–Female":"Deceased","1413":"1413","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1455":"1455","1421":"1421","1399":"1399","1375":"1375","1405":"1405","Hales, Norfolk, England":"Hales, Norfolk, England","Wood Norton, Norfolk, England":"Wood Norton, Norfolk, England","Blo'norton, Norfolk, England":"Blo'norton, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hales","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (widespread, especially in the southeast): from the genitive singular or nominative plural form of Old English <i>halh</i> ‘nook, recess’ (see   Hale  ).","Irish: when not of English origin, this may be a variant of   Healy   or   McHale  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hale","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived in a (usually remote) nook or corner of land, from Old English and Middle English <i>hale</i>, dative of <i>h(e)alh</i> ‘nook, hollow’, or a habitational name from a place so named such as Hale in Cheshire, Hampshire, Lancashire, Lincolnshire, Holme Hale (Norfolk), Hale Street (Kent), and Haile (Cumberland). In northern England the word often has a specialized meaning, denoting a piece of flat alluvial land by the side of a river, typically one deposited in a bend. See   Haugh  . In southeastern England it often referred to a patch of dry land in a fen. In some cases the surname may be a habitational name from any of several places in England named with this fossilized inflected form, which would originally have been preceded by a preposition, e.g. <i>in the hale</i> or <i>at the hale</i>. This surname is also established in south Wales.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Céile</b> (see   McHale  ).","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Halle  ."]},{"name":"Hayles","meanings":["English:","variant of   Hales  .","variant of   Ayles   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]},{"name":"Hailes","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Hailes in Colinton (Midlothian), originally in East Lothian, named from the Middle English genitive or plural form of <i>hall</i> ‘hall’.","English: variant of   Hales   (see also   Hayles  )."]}]},{"name":"Edmund","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protector’. It was borne by several early royal and saintly figures, including a 9th-century king of East Anglia killed by invading Danes, allegedly for his adherence to Christianity. In the 16th and 17th centuries, there was a good deal of interchange between <i>Edmund</i> and <i>Edward</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":55,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Edmund Hales was born in 1400, in Wood Norton, Norfolk, England as the son of Coroner Roger de Hales and miss Scogan. He married Mrs. Edmund Hales in 1421, in Blo'norton, Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in Blo'norton, Norfolk, England."},"et":{"1400–":"1400–Surnud","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1422–Female":"1422–Surnud","1375–1413":"1375–1413","–Female":"Surnud","1413":"1413","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1455":"1455","1421":"1421","1399":"1399","1375":"1375","1405":"1405","Hales, Norfolk, England":"Hales, Norfolk, England","Wood Norton, Norfolk, England":"Wood Norton, Norfolk, England","Blo'norton, Norfolk, England":"Blo'norton, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"1400–":"1400–Kuollut","1400–Male":"1400–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1405–Female":"1405–Kuollut","1422–Female":"1422–Kuollut","1375–1413":"1375–1413","–Female":"Kuollut","1413":"1413","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1455":"1455","1421":"1421","1399":"1399","1375":"1375","1405":"1405","Hales, Norfolk, England":"Hales, Norfolk, England","Wood Norton, Norfolk, England":"Wood Norton, Norfolk, England","Blo'norton, Norfolk, England":"Blo'norton, Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"1400–":"1400–Décédé","1400–Male":"1400–Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","1405–Female":"1405–Décédée","1422–Female":"1422–Décédée","1375–1413":"1375–1413","–Female":"Décédée","1413":"1413","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1455":"1455","1421":"1421","1399":"1399","1375":"1375","1405":"1405","Hales, Norfolk, England":"Hales, Norfolk, Angleterre","Wood Norton, Norfolk, England":"Wood Norton, Norfolk, Angleterre","Blo'norton, Norfolk, England":"Blo'norton, Norfolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Edmund Hales est né en 1400, à Wood Norton, Norfolk, Angleterre, fils de Coroner Roger de Hales et miss Scogan. Il a épousé Mrs. Edmund Hales en 1421, à Blo'norton, Norfolk, Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille. Il est décédé à Blo'norton, Norfolk, Angleterre."},"de":{"1400–":"1400–Verstorben","1400–Male":"1400–Verstorben","–Male":"Verst